<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-2-3">
    <title>Exercises</title>
   <exercise xml:id="ex-functions-exer">
    <title>Are they functions?</title>
        <webwork>
            <pg-code><![CDATA[
                loadMacros(
                "parserCheckboxList.pl",
                );

                $checks = CheckboxList(
                [
                    [
                    '\(x = ay-b\) for nonzero real numbers \(a,b\)',
                    '\(y = \sqrt{4-x^2}\)',
                    '\(x=e^{y-1}-8\)',
                    '\(x^2 + y^2 = r\) for \(r>0\)'
                    ],
                    'None of the above'
                ],
                [
                    '\(x = ay-b\) for nonzero real numbers \(a,b\)',
                    '\(y = \sqrt{4-x^2}\)',
                    '\(x=e^{y-1}-8\)'
                ],
                labels => "ABC",
                displayLabels => 1
                );
                ]]>
            </pg-code>

            <statement>
            <p>
                Determine which of the following equations represent functions on their implied domains.
                Assume <m>x</m> is the input variable, and <m>y</m> is the output variable.
            </p>

            <p>
                <var name="$checks" form="checkboxes"/>
            </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>x=ay-b</m> can be rearranged as <m>y = \frac{1}{a}x + \frac{b}{a}</m>.
                    Since <m>a\ne 0</m>, this is simply a line, which is a function.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>y = \sqrt{4-x^2}</m> is already written in functional form.
                    It can be seen that a single value for <m>x</m> with <m>-2\leq x \leq 2</m> will yield a single output value <m>y</m>.
                    Graphically, this is the top half of a circle.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Solving <m>x^2 + y^2 = r</m> for <m>y</m> yields <m>y = \pm \sqrt{r-x^2}</m>.
                    This is not a function.
                    For example, <m>x=0</m> would give <m>y = \sqrt{r}</m> or <m>-\sqrt{r}</m>.
                    Graphically, this is a circle with radius <m>\sqrt{r}</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>x = e^{y-1}-8</m> can be rearranged as <m>y = \ln(x+8) + 1</m>.
                    This is a logarithmic function.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-one-to-one-exer">
    <title>Are they One-to-One?</title>
        <webwork>
            <pg-code><![CDATA[
                loadMacros(
                "parserCheckboxList.pl",
                );

                $checks = CheckboxList(
                [
                    [
                    '\(f(x) = \sqrt[3]{x}\)',
                    '\(g(x) = \sin(x)\) on the restricted domain \([0,\pi]\)',
                    '\(h(x) = e^{x^2}\)',
                    '\(r(x) = |5-x|\)',
                    '\(k(x) = \ln(5x) + 3\)'
                    ],
                    'None of the above'
                ],
                [
                    '\(f(x) = \sqrt[3]{x}\)',
                    '\(k(x) = \ln(5x) + 3\)'
                ],
                labels => "ABC",
                displayLabels => 1
                );
                ]]>
            </pg-code>

            <statement>
            <p>
                Determine which of the following functions are one-to-one.
            </p>

            <p>
                <var name="$checks" form="checkboxes"/>
            </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) = \sqrt[3]{x}</m> is one-to-one.  
                    Power functions of the form <m>x^p</m> or <m>x^{\drac{1}{p}}</m> will be one-to-one when <m>p</m> is odd.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>g(x) = \sin(x)</m> is not one-to-one on the domain <m>[0,\pi]</m>.
                    For example, <m>g(0) \sin(0) = 0 = \sin(\pi) = g(\pi)</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>h(x) = e^{x^2}</m> is not one-to-one.
                    For example, <m>h(1) = h(-1) = e</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>r(x) = |5-x|</m> is not one-to-one.
                    For example, <m>r(4) = r(6) = 1</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>k(x) = \ln(5x)+3</m> is one-to-one.
                    It is a logarithmic function shifted up 3 units.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-find-inverses">
        <title>Find the Inverses</title>
            <webwork>
                <pg-code><![CDATA[
                    Context("Numeric");
                    Context()->variables->are(x=>"Real");

                    $ans_f = Formula("(x^3 + 1)/2");
                    $ans_g = Formula("-exp((x-1)/3)/4");

                    $ans_h = Formula("(ln(x)/ln(5))^(1/3)");

                    $ans_r = Formula("1/x");
                        ]]>
                </pg-code>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Determine the inverses of the following functions.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{2x-1}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>f^{-1}(x)=</m>
                                    <var name="$ans_f" width="30"/>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>g(x)=3\ln(-4x)+1</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>g^{-1}(x)=</m>
                                    <var name="$ans_g" width="30"/>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>h(x)=5^{x^3}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>h^{-1}(x)=</m>
                                    <var name="$ans_h" width="30"/>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>r(x)=\frac{1}{x}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>r^{-1}(x)=</m>
                                    <var name="$ans_r" width="30"/>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The inverse functions are:
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        \begin{aligned}
                                            y &amp; = \sqrt[3]{2x-1}\\
                                            y^3 &amp; = 2x-1\\
                                            y^3 + 1 &amp; = 2x\\
                                            \frac{1}{2}y^3 + \frac{1}{2} &amp; x\\
                                            y &amp; = \frac{1}{2}x^3 + \frac{1}{2} \text{ (swap variables)}\\
                                            f^{-1} &amp; = \frac{1}{2}x^3 + \frac{1}{2}
                                        \end{aligned}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        \begin{aligned}
                                            y &amp; = 3ln(-4x)+1\\
                                            y-1 &amp; = 3\ln(-4x)\\
                                            \frac{1}{3}y-\frac{1}{3} &amp; = \ln(-4x)\\
                                            e^{\frac{1}{3}y - \frac{1}{3}} &amp; -4x\\
                                            -\frac{1}{4}e^{\frac{1}{3}y - \frac{1}{3}} &amp; = x\\
                                            y &amp; = -\frac{1}{4}e^{\frac{1}{3}x - \frac{1}{3}} \text{ (swap variables)}\\
                                            g^{-1}(x) &amp; = -\frac{1}{4}e^{\frac{1}{3}x - \frac{1}{3}}
                                        \end{aligned}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        \begin{aligned}
                                            y &amp; = 5^{x^3}\\
                                            \ln(y) &amp; = \ln\left(5^{x^3}\right) = \ln(5)x^3\\
                                            \frac{\ln(y)}{\ln(5)} &amp; = x^3\\
                                            \sqrt[3]{\frac{\ln(y)}{\ln(5)}} &amp; = x\\
                                            y &amp; = \sqrt[3]{\frac{\ln(x)}{\ln(5)}} \text{ (swap variables)}\\
                                            h^{-1}(x) &amp; = \sqrt[3]{\frac{\ln(x)}{\ln(5)}}
                                        \end{aligned}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        \begin{aligned}
                                            y &amp; = \frac{1}{x}\\
                                            \frac{1}{y} &amp; = x\\
                                            y &amp; = \frac{1}{x} \text{ (swap variables)}\\
                                            r^{-1}(x) &amp; = \frac{1}{x}
                                        \end{aligned}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
    </exercise>

     <exercise xml:id="ex-break-up-function">
        <title>Break the Domain</title>
            <webwork>
                <pg-code><![CDATA[
                    Context("Numeric");
                    Context()->variables->are(x=>"Real");

                    $ans_f = Formula("3-2x");
                    $ans_g = Formula("2x-3");

                    $ans_h = Formula("-0.5x+1.5");

                    $ans_r = Formula("0.5x+1.5");
                        ]]>
                </pg-code>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(x) = |3-2x|</m> is not invertible.  Break the domain of $f$ into two components on which each component is invertible.  Find the inverse function for each invertible segment.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        On the restricted domain <m>[1.5,\infty)</m>, <m>f(x)</m> is equal to the function <m>g(x) = </m> <var name="$ans_g" width="30"/>, 
                        and has an inverse function of <m>g^{-1} = </m> <var name="$ans_r" width="30"/>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        On the restricted domain <m>(-\infty, 1.5)</m>, <m>f(x)</m> is equal to the function <m>h(x) = </m> <var name="$ans_f" width="30"/>, 
                        and has an inverse function of <m>h^{-1} = </m> <var name="$ans_h" width="30"/>.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        In general, for a function <m>f(x)</m>, <m>|f(x)| = \pm f(x)</m>.
                        So, our two functions are <m>3-2x</m> and <m>-(3-2x) = 2x-3</m>.
                        These are on the domains <m>(-\infty,1.5)</m> and <m>[1.5,\infty)</m>, respectively.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        To find the inverses:
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \begin{aligned}
                                y &amp; = 2x-3\\
                                y+3 &amp; = 2x\\
                                \frac{1}{2}y + \frac{3}{2} &amp; = x\\
                                y &amp; = \frac{1}{2}x + \frac{3}{2} \text{ (swap the variables)}\\
                            \end{aligned}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        and
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \begin{aligned}
                                y &amp; = 3-2x\\
                                y-3 &amp; = -2x\\
                                -\frac{1}{2}y + \frac{3}{2} &amp; = x\\
                                y &amp; = -\frac{1}{2}x + \frac{3}{2} \text{ (swap the variables)}\\
                            \end{aligned}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
    </exercise>
</subsection>